Docker Image Creation Experiment (Two Methods)

This experiment demonstrates two ways to create Docker images:

Using docker commit

Using a Dockerfile

PART A: Create Image Using docker commit

Pull Ubuntu image
docker pull ubuntu:latest

Run Ubuntu container
docker run -it --name mycontainer ubuntu:latest

Inside the container create a file
cat > myfile.txt
Hello from my custom image!
(Press Ctrl + D)

Exit the container
exit

Create an image from the container
docker commit mycontainer myimage:v1

Verify the created image
docker images

Run a new container from the committed image
docker run -it myimage:v1

Push PART A Image to Docker Hub

Login to Docker Hub
docker login

Tag the image (replace yourusername)
docker tag myimage:v1 yourusername/myimage:v1

Push the image
docker push yourusername/myimage:v1

PART B: Create Image Using Dockerfile

Create a new folder
mkdir mydockerfileimages
cd mydockerfileimages

Create a message file
notepad message.txt

Content of message.txt:
This image was created using Dockerfile.

Create a Dockerfile
notepad Dockerfile

Content of Dockerfile:
FROM ubuntu:latest
WORKDIR /
COPY message.txt /message.txt
CMD ["/bin/bash"]

If Notepad saved it as Dockerfile.txt rename it:
rename-item Dockerfile.txt Dockerfile

Verify files
ls

Build the image
docker build -t mydockerfileimage:v1 .

Verify the image
docker images

Run container from the Dockerfile image
docker run -it mydockerfileimage:v1

Check the copied file inside the container
cat /message.txt

Push PART B Image to Docker Hub

Tag the Dockerfile image
docker tag mydockerfileimage:v1 yourusername/mydockerfileimage:v1

Push the image
docker push yourusername/mydockerfileimage:v1
